## ğŸŒ¼ 2. **Aggregation (has-a relationship)**

### ğŸ”¹ Concept:

Aggregation ek **"whole-part"** relation hota hai, jisme part independent hota hai.
Yani agar â€œwholeâ€ class destroy ho jaaye, toh â€œpartâ€ fir bhi exist kar sakta hai.
Yeh **weak relationship** hota hai.

**Example:**
Ek `Library` ke paas multiple `Books` hote hain â€” agar library band ho jaaye, books fir bhi exist karti hain.

### ğŸ”¹ UML Diagram

```
Library â—Šâ€”â€” Book
```

### ğŸ”¹ Code:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

class Book {
public:
    string title;
    Book(string t) { title = t; }
};

class Library {
public:
    string name;
    vector<Book*> books;  // aggregation (pointer to book)

    Library(string n) { name = n; }

    void addBook(Book* b) {
        books.push_back(b);
    }

    void showBooks() {
        cout << name << " Library has:" << endl;
        for (auto b : books)
            cout << "- " << b->title << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Book b1("C++ Basics");
    Book b2("Data Structures");
    Library l("Central");

    l.addBook(&b1);
    l.addBook(&b2);
    l.showBooks();
    return 0;
}
```

### ğŸ”¹ Output:

```
Central Library has:
- C++ Basics
- Data Structures
```

### ğŸ”¹ Explanation:

Yahan `Library` **has-a** `Book`, but agar library delete ho gayi toh books alag se exist kar sakti hain.
Yeh **Aggregation** ka example hai.

---

## ğŸŒ» 3. **Composition (strong has-a relationship)**

### ğŸ”¹ Concept:

Composition bhi **â€œhas-aâ€** relationship hai, lekin yeh **strong** version hota hai.
Agar â€œwholeâ€ destroy ho gaya, toh â€œpartâ€ bhi destroy ho jaata hai.

**Example:**
Ek `House` ke andar `Room` hote hain â€” agar house destroy ho gaya, toh rooms bhi khatam.

### ğŸ”¹ UML Diagram

```
House â—†â€”â€” Room
```

### ğŸ”¹ Code:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

class Room {
public:
    string roomName;
    Room(string name) { roomName = name; }
};

class House {
private:
    vector<Room> rooms; // composition: direct object
public:
    void addRoom(string name) {
        rooms.push_back(Room(name));
    }

    void showRooms() {
        cout << "House has:" << endl;
        for (auto &r : rooms)
            cout << "- " << r.roomName << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    House h;
    h.addRoom("Bedroom");
    h.addRoom("Kitchen");
    h.showRooms();
    return 0;
}
```

### ğŸ”¹ Output:

```
House has:
- Bedroom
- Kitchen
```

### ğŸ”¹ Explanation:

`House` ke andar `Room` objects directly exist karte hain.
Agar house delete ho jaaye, toh rooms bhi khatam â€” thatâ€™s **Composition**.

